qas.question: What was Elizabeth primarily interested in?
Who did Elizabeth I collaborate with?
What was the goal of the first trading companies?
What company was charted in 1600 for trade to the East Indies?

context: Elizabeth I of <a0_0>England<a0_0/>, primarily interested in <a1_0>trade with the east<a1_0/>, collaborated with <a2_0>English merchants<a2_0/> to form the first trading companies to the far-flung regions, using their own jargon. Their goals were to <a3_0>obtain trading concessions by treaty<a3_0/>. The queen chartered the Company of Merchants of the Levant, shortened to Levant Company, and soon known also as The Turkey Company, in 1581. In 1582, the ship The Great Susan transported the first ambassador, William Harebone, to the Ottoman Porte (government of the Ottoman Empire) at Constantinople. Compared to Anatolia, Levant also means "land of the rising sun," but where Anatolia always only meant the projection of land currently occupied by the Republic of Turkey, Levant meant anywhere in the domain ruled by the Ottoman Porte. <a4_0>The East India Company<a4_0/> (short for a much longer formal name) was chartered in 1600 for trade to the East Indies.
